4 

Gender pay gap as at 31 March 2017 

Mean: average hourly rate of pay and percentage difference 

           

                     Gap: 3.25%, £0.50 per hour               

     

                                                

         £15.58                                           

 

  

 

 £15.08 

Based on the required criteria; a calculation of the data shows that as at 31 March 
2017 the mean pay for men was £15.58 per hour and for women was £15.08 per 
hour.  This equates to an additional 3.25% for men.  

The mean difference recorded at CDC is 14.45% less than the national public sector 
mean pay gap which is 17.7% (Office for National Statistics – ASHE). 

Median: middle hourly rate of pay and percentage difference 

 

                      Gap: 6.89%, £0.98 per hour 

           

                                                 

        £14.22                                               

 

 

 

 £13.24 

The median pay for men was £14.22 at 31 March 2018, compared to £13.24 for 
women.  This means that men earned an average of £0.98 per hour more than 
women, which equates to a median difference of 6.89%. 

The median difference recorded at CDC is 12.51% less than the national public 
sector median pay gap which is 19.4% (Office for National Statistics – ASHE). 

Proportion of men and women receiving bonuses 

CDC does not operate any performance related pay or bonus schemes and therefore 
has no bonus gender pay gap. 

 

 

 

 

