6 

 

 

There are a higher proportion of men in the upper and upper middle quartiles; with 
the highest difference recorded in the upper middle quartile where the workforce 
breakdown for this category shows almost 5.5% more men than women. 

Overall within CDC our mean, median and quartile findings are positive, reflecting a 
balanced gender pay gap report within our workforce. With our overall workforce 
split between men and women as 51:49; this serves as a useful benchmark by which 
to compare each pay quartile. 

CDC operate a robust job evaluation process and this is apparent through the fact 
that the highest difference in any quartile is 5.5%.  We will ensure that job grades 
continue to be determined through objective analysis and job evaluation to maintain 
the integrity of the pay and grading system. 

Family friendly policies and flexible working ensures that CDC can both attract and 
retain staff in a competitive job market and in a geographical area with low 
unemployment. 

The gender pay gap data will be analysed on an annual basis and a comparison of 
figures will be completed year on year.  The Senior Management Team will continue 
to review and monitor this data. 

 

 

 

